It’s no surprise that Cream Parlor won New Times “Best Of Miami” award for best ice-cream parlor a couple of years ago. I think it should win every year. Indeed, Cream Parlor should win many awards as it is more than a fabulous ice-cream parlor (although it does have the most impressive, inventive and delicious array of ice-cream choices imaginable). Cream Parlor is also a tea room, a great place to grab the best cup of coffee in Miami, as well as the perfect choice for breakfast or lunch or an early dinner with its stellar menu of delicious options which includes salads, sandwiches, bowls, paninis, tartines and more (cookies, cake, shakes and of course ice-cream). It is the charmer of the Upper Eastside, located just a few blocks north of the main MiMo district, with a bright exterior which invokes an old-time ice-cream parlor. I’ve been popping into this lovely and popular spot since it opened several years ago. This past weekend I was there twice and enjoyed great coffee, a delicious wrap and yummy ice-cream. The robin egg blue interior is an eclectic, colorful and cozy mixture of vintage finds and curiosities. Lovely mismatched china plates and cups are used to serve the food and beverages. The staff are wonderful and the owner, Ainsley, always greets everyone who comes through the door with a warm hello. Cream Parlor is the most welcoming treasure on Biscayne Boulevard if not the whole of Miami. It’s unlike anywhere else in town and I continue to recommend it over and over again!

I had the ice cream and it was that gold ole' fashion ice cream feel to it, and nicely presented in a waffle cone (I don't recall the name flavor but it was blue) my friend had coffee (lactose issues!) We spent about 90 mins there (middle of afternoon) and felt we were overstaying our welcome and jokingly told them we weren't moving in and would leave soon , but the staff was so friendly and told us to not even give a  second thought. They had vanilla with chocolate covered almonds. I also had the chocolate chip toffee cookie. This is a large homemade cookie for $1.75. Next time I want to try the huge brownie I saw. They have a good menu too. There is an outside back patio. We parked in the small Free lot on the south side of building. There is metered street parking. I can't say enough nice things about this restaurant, it's staff and ownership!! The ambiance and decorative style is so eclectic and interesting that I find something new every time I shift my sight. The staff and owners are very welcoming and friendly, always offering compliments and genuine interest when you speak to them. The ice cream is delicious of course, as are the sandwiches, bowls, and all of their drinks. I love how creative they are with their ingredients in the ice cream and coffees in particular, and their presentation is always top notch! This is all before even touching on the outdoor patio which is like stepping into a quiet little Oasis of comfort filled with bright colors. They are very dog and kid friendly but I would also recommend this spot for an afternoon date or even to get some work done while sipping their delicious coffees. I love cream parlor and only wish I lived a little closer to it so it could be a more regular stop for me!

I stepped into Cream because many friends suggested this cute little ice cream shop. The people working behind the counter were very friendly and upbeat. They allow me to sample whatever ice creams were available. They all tasted so good that it was hard to choose just one. I chose one of the ice creams that was the special of the day. It was very creamy and delicious, and the waffle cone bowl was also delicious.  As I looked around inside, the decor that lined the walls and shelves brought back memories of my childhood with board games, gum balls, china tea cups, and other fun, cute items. The back patio seating area looked cozy and homey. I look forward to visiting again.

The fact they're pet friendly assures the fifth star with me!  I met with a couple of friends for a long weekend brunch Sunday, my first time here. I'd driven by before, and thought this was just an ice cream spot but was very pleasantly surprised that they offer a full menu. The inside is cozy with lots of funky art focusing on the 80s, plus silverware you'd find at your abuelas. Kudos for the creative decor!  Their food menu is mostly salads and sandwiches,  and two plates caught my eye. You have to try their lentils (typically one of my favorite bean soups). However, Cream serves more as a bean salad to which they balance sriracha and honey. The sweet taste drew me, and the heat satisfied my taste buds. Portion size was also generous.  With all the heat, I needed to cool down some. Their prosciutto tartine did just that. With plenty of ham on fresh greens and creamy goat cheese on sweet apricot jam I enjoyed a delicious summer brunch.  Though I didn't bring Princess Luna, I saw that it was dog friendly (with a nice patio) with a couple of other clients and their fluffy woofers. Very sweet owner Ainsley confirmed as much.
